<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="200" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="7.[772,1365,3058,3479]" pageId="7" pageNumber="200">
Although C. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Broom" authorityYear="1907" box="[978,1071,3172,3205]" class="Mammalia" family="Chrysochloridae" genus="Chrysochloris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Afrosoricida" pageId="7" pageNumber="200" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sclateri">sclateri</taxonomicName>
is considered subspecifically distinct from C. 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Broom" baseAuthorityYear="1907" box="[1206,1320,3215,3244]" class="Mammalia" family="Chrysochloridae" genus="Chlorotalpa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Afrosoricida" pageId="7" pageNumber="200" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="duthieae">duthieae</taxonomicName>
by some authors, it is now considered a distinct species due to consistent differences in pelage color, chromosomal properties, malleus morphology, and habitat selection. Four subspecies recognized.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
